29.29        Software Requirements Specification (SRS)
29.29.1      The Software Requirements Specification (SRS) shall be compliant to IEEE
             Std 830-1998, Recommended Practice for Software Requirements
             Specifications, , as modified by IEEE 1558-2004. The followings present
             examples of SRS content:


(a)          Functional and capability specifications including performance, physical
             characteristics, and environmental conditions under which the software is to
             perform;


(b)          Specification of Interfaces external to the software including:


( i )        the input and output communication ports;


( i i )         communication protocols, procedures and performance;


( i i i )    exception handling and recovery;


( i v )     message formats (for example maximum message length) and message
             frequency.

(c)          Safety specifications, where applicable, including :


( i )        software failure detection, identification and isolation;


( i i )        remedial procedures;


(iii) redundancy;


( i v )    failsafe operation;


( v )     fall-back procedures and reconstruction of destroyed or incorrectly altered
             data;


(d)          Human-factors engineering specifications, where applicable, including :

(c)        Data interfaces of the module including :


(i)        input / output parameters - any input and output parameters passed during the
           activation and return from the module and shall be related to the entry and exit
           conditions;


( i i )    any absolutes or constants used;


( i i i ) any global variables used;


( i v ) any local variables used within the module's components;

